    "summary": "Bad idea — translation friction IS the point",
    "content": "Bad idea. The translation difficulty IS the point. If the text is making an argument about how conceptual systems work, then showing a genuinely foreign conceptual system — one where the reader has to slow down and feel the friction — is far more powerful than a Western example they'd glide past without noticing the very phenomenon being described.\n\nThe translation apparatus (constitutive character, TNs, glosses) isn't a bug, it's a feature. It enacts what it describes: the reader experiences firsthand how concepts resist clean mapping across frameworks. A Western example would make the passage easier to read but would undercut its epistemic force.\n\nKeep the Chinese example in the main text. The apparatus supports comprehension without domesticating the content."
  }
}
